LOCAL PIPELINE TARIFF CONTAINING RULES AND REGULATIONS GOVERNING THE INTERSTATE TRANSPORTATION OF LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS BY PIPELINE GENERAL APPLICATION [N] SPECIAL PERMISSION REQUESTED Issued on less than one days' notice under authority of 18 C.F.R. ? 341.14. 1 ABBREVIATIONS AND DEFINITIONS Capitalized terms in this tariff shall have the following meanings: "ASTM" means American Society for Testing and Materials. "Barrel" means forty-two (42) United States gallons at sixty degrees (60?) Fahrenheit and equilibrium vapor pressure. "Butane" means a hydrocarbon product composed predominantly of butane (including n-butane and isobutane) and conforming to the specifications for refinery grade butane as designated in ASTM Standard Specification D1835-05 or later revision in all respects excepting moisture content which shall be subject to Carrier's determination as to operational feasibility. "Carrier" means [W] Spire NGL, Inc. Laclede Pipeline Company "Deficiency Contract" means a contract between Carrier and a Shipper that entitles the Shipper to receive certain discounts stated in Carrier's F.E.R.C. tariff applicable to LPG tendered in amounts greater than a stated minimum annual volume and obligates Shipper to incur deficiency obligations with respect to the failure to tender LPG at levels below the stated minimum volume. "FERC" means Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. "G.P.A." means the Gas Processors Association. "LPG" means Liquefied Petroleum Gas conforming to N.G.P.A. Publication 2140 (N.P.G.A. Liquefied Petroleum Gas Specifications and Test Methods) as revised in 1997 or later revisions. "Point of Destination" means the specific location or locations on Carrier's pipeline system as designated in this tariff to which Carrier delivers LPG. "Point of Origin" means the specific location or locations on Carrier's pipeline system as designated in this tariff at which Carrier accepts LPG for transportation. "Propane" means a hydrocarbon product composed predominantly of propane and conforming to the definition of and specifications for "Propane HD-5" as contained in G.P.A. Publication 2140 (G.P.A. Liquefied Petroleum Gas Specifications and Test Methods) as revised in 1997 or later revisions in all respects excepting moisture content which shall be subject to Carrier's determination as to operational feasibility. "Shipper" means the party or parties who contract with Carrier for the transportation of LPG under the terms of this tariff. 5 COMMODITY The Tariff covers the transportation of LPG by Carrier, and no commodity other than LPG will be transported under the Tariff. 10 DELIVERY AND ACCEPTANCE LPG will be accepted for transportation only when tendered In accordance with all relevant provisions of the Tariff and Nominated for delivery to the Shipper at one or more delivery points. Carrier shall have no obligation to accept LPG for transportation if such LPG contains free water or other impurities. 20 SCHEDULING AND SHIPMENTS A Shipper desiring to transport LPG shall furnish a shipment nomination notice to Carrier specifying Point of Origin, Point of Destination, and volume by the 25th day of the month prior to the month in which transportation is requested. If Shipper does not furnish such a nomination notice, Carrier shall be under no obligation to accept LPG for transportation. If space is available and operating conditions permit, Carrier may, at its reasonable and not unduly discriminatory discretion, accept nominations, or revised nominations, submitted after the 25th day of the preceding month. If Shipper is required to revise a nomination during a month due to unforeseen weather-related or demand-related changes, Carrier will accommodate such fluctuations, including supplemental nominations, to the full extent operationally feasible. If requested by Carrier, Shipper shall furnish Carrier with a schedule of the expected deliveries at origin and withdrawals at destination, setting forth Shipper's best estimate of daily rate of deliveries and withdrawals and dates on which such withdrawals shall commence. Acceptance of such schedule shall not constitute an obligation, legal or otherwise, on the part of Carrier to meet such schedule. 25 CONFIRMATION OF SUPPLY SOURCE Except with respect to revised nominations made pursuant to Item No. 20, Shipper shall confirm Shipper's LPG supply source to Carrier no less than three working days and no more than five working days prior to delivering LPG to Carrier's Point of Origin. Carrier shall be under no obligation to accept LPG if Shipper does not so confirm Shipper's LPG supply source. 30 FACILITIES AT ORIGIN AND DESTINATION Carrier shall provide such facilities at the Points of Origin and Points of Destination as it deems necessary for the operation of the pipeline. Shipments will be accepted for transportation by Carrier only when Shipper has provided facilities satisfactory to Carrier capable of (i) delivering LPG into such Point of Origin at pressures and pumping rates required by Carrier and (ii) receiving LPG into such Point of Destination at pressures and pumping rates required by Carrier. Upon receiving a reasonable request for a new interconnection by a potential or current Shipper, Carrier will establish an Interconnection Policy to be incorporated by reference in this Tariff. Separate agreements, if applicable, in association with pipeline connections or other facilities ancillary to the Carrier's pipeline system and in accordance with this tariff shall be required of any shipper or consignee before any obligation to provide transportation shall arise. For each pipeline connection, Shipper shall provide semi-annual documentation to Carrier that demonstrates compliance with the regulations of the U.S. Department of Transportation (49 CFR Part 195.428) for overpressure protection consistent with Carrier's Maximum Allowable Operating Pressure (MAOP). 35 SHIPMENT SIZE A minimum shipment of ten thousand (10,000) barrels of the same quality and specifications of LPG shall be accepted for transportation at one Point of Origin from one Shipper. Shipper shall establish the ability to meet the minimum tender requirements before any duty to undertake transportation shall arise.
Carrier may elect to accept a shipment of less than ten thousand (10,000) barrels of the same quality and specifications of LPG for transportation at one Point of Origin from one Shipper, but, if Carrier makes such election, such shipment may be received subject to delay, at Carrier's discretion, until Carrier has accumulated at the same Point of Origin ten thousand (10,000) barrels of LPG of the same specifications from the same or other Shippers.
Carrier will not be required to accept a shipment of greater than two hundred thousand (200,000) barrels of the same quality and specifications of LPG for transportation at one Point of Origin from one Shipper, but Carrier will accept such a shipment if operationally feasible. 40 QUALITY WARRANTY AND TESTING Shipper warrants that all LPG tendered to Carrier complies with Carrier's specifications as set forth in the definition of "LPG" in Item 1. Carrier may require Shipper to furnish a certificate setting forth in detail specifications of each shipment of LPG tendered for transportation under this tariff, and Shipper shall be liable, and shall indemnify Carrier and other Shippers, for any contamination or damage to other LPG in Carrier's custody, or to Carrier's pipeline or other facilities caused by failure of the LPG so received from Shipper to meet either Carrier's specifications for "LPG" or to meet the specifications stated in Shipper's certificate. Carrier may, but shall not be required to, sample and/or test any shipment prior to acceptance or during or after receipt of shipment, and in the event of variance between the definition of LPG in Item 1 or the specifications contained in said certificate and the specifications indicated by Carrier's test, Carrier's test results shall prevail and be determinative as to whether the shipment meets Carrier's required specifications. 45 INDEMNIFICATION Shipper acknowledges and represents that it is knowledgeable in the chemical and physical properties of LPG and unodorized LPG and the limitations, delivery, storage, use, transportation, handling, and sale of LPG, whether odorized or not odorized, and covenants and warrants that it will provide to its consignees such information and warnings that are necessary and appropriate for the proper delivery, storage, use, transportation, handling, and sale of such LPG. Carrier agrees to provide Shipper with warning brochures as Shipper may request during the term of this tariff. Shipper agrees to defend, indemnify, and hold harmless Carrier, its affiliates and subsidiaries, and its and their respective directors, officers, agents, and employees (collectively, "Carrier Indemnities") from and against any and all liabilities or claims, injuries or illnesses (including death resulting there from), or property damage, or fines, penalties, or assessments by any governmental authority, or losses, costs or expenses (including costs of defense, settlement and reasonable attorneys' fees), which are directly or indirectly caused by Shipper's failure to provide to its employees, agents, invitees, contractors, subcontractors, licensees, consignees, and shippers adequate warnings concerning LPG and odorant. The Carrier Indemnities shall have a right to notice of any settlement, and Shipper shall not execute or otherwise agree to any settlement or consent decree which requires the payment of money or imposes any obligations or restrictions on Carrier's operations without Carrier Indemnities' prior written consent. The provision of this Item 45 shall survive the termination or expiration of this tariff. 50 MEASUREMENT Measurement of all LPG shipped shall be determined by Shipper's meter, or, at the election of Carrier, by Carrier's meter. Such meter shall be operated in accordance with the American Petroleum Institute (API) Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards. Meters shall be gauged or proven periodically in conformance with such standards. Statements of such meter proving shall be kept on file for review by Shipper or Carrier upon request. LPG will be received and delivered on the basis of volume corrections for temperature from observed temperatures to sixty degrees (60?) Fahrenheit using the factors for specific gravity conversion and volume correction appearing in Table 34, ASTM-IP Petroleum Measurement Tables, ASTM Designation 1250 (latest revision). LPG will be received and delivered on the basis of volume corrections for compressibility in accordance with API Standard No. 1101, Table II (latest revision). The balance will be the net quantities deliverable. 55 IDENTITY OF SHIPMENTS Carrier shall not maintain identity of LPG shipments consisting of Propane, but will deliver from Carrier's common stream. LPG shipments consisting of Butane will be delivered in segregated batches. A Shipper nominating a Butane shipment must arrange for the displacement of Propane out of the Carrier's system and for the return of such displaced Propane upon delivery of the Butane shipment. Shippers tendering Butane may be required to supply buffer material for their shipments. 60 LPG SUBJECT TO LIENS OR INVOLVED IN LITIGATION Carrier shall have the right to reject any LPG offered for transportation which may be involved in litigation, or the title of which may be in dispute, or which may be encumbered by a lien or charge of any kind, and Carrier may require of the Shipper satisfactory evidence of Shipper's perfect and unencumbered title and/or satisfactory bond indemnifying Carrier against any and all losses. Shipment notices submitted by a Shipper shall be considered as warranties of title and absences of encumbrance and Carrier shall have no obligation to make inquiry with respect thereto. No acceptance of LPG by Carrier shall constitute a waiver or subordination of Carrier's lien or any other rights thereunder or under this tariff. 65 PAYMENT OFCARRIER CHARGES AND CARRIER'S LIEN Transportation fees and all other lawful charges accruing on LPG accepted for transportation shall be assessed by Carrier at the rates specified in this tariff on the basis of quantities of LPG received at a Point of Origin and delivered at a Point of Destination. Carrier shall, on or before the ninth (9th) business day of each month, render to Shipper an invoice for each LPG Shipment during the preceding month. As used in this Section 65, "render" is defined as postmarked, time-stamped and delivered to the designated site. Shipper shall pay to Carrier at the address indicated an the invoice or, if directed by Carrier, by wire transfer to a bank designated by Carrier, the amount due Carrier for services provided during the appropriate calendar month as reflected in the billing described above, within ten (10) calendar days after the date of receipt of such billing. For purposes of this Section, the bill is deemed to be received by Shipper three (3) days after the postmark date if sent by mail. The invoice number should be identified on all payments and the Shipper should submit supporting documentation identifying what is being paid. Carrier shall apply payment per such supporting documentation. If payment differs from the invoiced amount, remittance detail should be provided with the payment except when payment is made by electronic funds transfer, in which case the remittance detail is due within two (2) business days of the payment due date. Should Shipper fail to pay any undisputed portion of any bill as herein provided when such amount is due, interest on the unpaid portion of the bill shall accrue at the maximum allowable interest permitted under the Commission's Regulations. For any amount to be considered "disputed," Shipper must provide appropriate documentation supporting and identifying the basis for the dispute. If Shipper fails to make payment in accordance with this Section, Carrier may, in addition to any other remedy it may have under this Tariff or under commercial law: (1) suspend deliveries (2) offset such deficient payments against any payments, refunds or credits owed by Carrier to Shipper. Carrier shall have a lien and security interest to the fullest extent permitted by law on all LPG in its custody belonging to Shipper to secure payment of all current and unpaid transportation charges and any other lawful charges due from Shipper to Carrier. If an invoice for transportation or other lawful charges is not paid to Carrier in full when due, the Shipper shall pay to Carrier interest on the outstanding amount from the original invoice date until paid at an annual rate equal to the lesser of six percent (6%) over the prime interest rate as published by the Wall Street Journal as of the invoice date or the highest lawful rate permitted. In addition and notwithstanding interest accrued and due on overdue invoices, if invoices due Carrier are unpaid, Carrier or Carrier's agent shall have the right to sell LPG of Shipper's in Carrier's custody at a public or private sale, on any day not a legal holiday and upon not less than forty-eight (48) hours notice to Shipper. Said notice to Shipper shall include the time and place of the sale, and the quantity and location of the LPG to be sold. Transportation and all other lawful charges due from Shipper to Carrier, including all of Carrier's expenses of such sale and expenses incidental to such sale, shall be paid to Carrier from the proceeds of the sale, and the balance, if any, shall be remitted to the Shipper. If the proceeds of such sale are not sufficient to pay the transportation and other lawful charges of the Carrier, including expenses of sale, due from Shipper to Carrier, then Shipper shall remain liable to Carrier for the unpaid balance. 70 CLAIMS, SUITS, TIME FOR FILING As a condition precedent to recovery, claims must be made in writing to Carrier within nine (9) months after receipt of delivery of the Shipment, or, in case of a failure to make delivery in accordance with this tariff, then within nine (9) months after a reasonable time for delivery has elapsed. Suit against Carrier shall be instituted only within two (2) years and one (1) day from the day when notice in writing is given by Carrier to the claimant that Carrier has disallowed the claim or any part thereof specified in the notice. Where claims for loss or damage are not filed or suits are not instituted thereon in accordance with the foregoing provisions, such claims will not be paid and Carrier shall not be liable therefore. 75 APPLICATION OF RATES LPG transported pursuant to this tariff shall be subject to rates, rules, and regulations governing the transportation of LPG that are in effect on the date such LPG is received by Carrier. 80 CHARGE FOR SPILL COMPENSATION ACTS AND REGULATIONS In addition to transportation and all other charges accruing on LPG accepted for transportation, a per Barrel charge shall be assessed and collected in the amount of any tax, fee, levy, or other charge against Carrier in connection with such LPG pursuant to any federal, state, or local law or regulation which imposes a tax, fee, levy, or other charge on the receipt, delivery, transfer, storage, or transportation of such LPG for the purpose of creating a fund for the prevention, containment, clean up and/or removal of spills, the reimbursement of persons sustaining loss therefrom or any other lawful purpose. Carrier shall be under no obligation to contest or protest on behalf of a Shipper the legality of such tax, fee, levy, or other charge. Carrier shall publish in this Tariff any such tax, fee, levy or such charges prior to billing the applicable Shipper(s). 85 DIVERSION Diversion of LPG while in transit from a Point of Origin to a Point of Destination different from the Point of Destination agreed to at the time of receipt of the LPG may be made if requested by the Shipper prior to delivery at the original Point of Destination, subject to applicable rate, rules, regulations, and Carrier's system capabilities. 90 FORCE MAJEURE If either Carrier or Shipper fails to perform any obligations under the Tariff due to an event of Force Majeure, then such failure shall be deemed not to be a breach of such obligations. The term "Force Majeure," as employed herein and for all purposes relating hereto, shall mean any act of God, war, civil insurrection or disobedience, acts of public enemy, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, accidents, blockades, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, explosions, fires, floods, civil disturbances, terrorism, the act, regulation, order, direction or requisition of any governmental or other authority having jurisdiction, or other cause whether of the kind enumerated or otherwise which is beyond the control of the applicable Party and which by the exercise of due diligence such Party is unable to prevent or overcome. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the following shall not be events of Force Majeure: (i) insufficiency of Shipper's LPG supplies; or (ii) lack of funds. A Party that fails to perform any obligations under the Tariff where such failure is caused by an event of Force Majeure shall promptly remedy the cause of the Force Majeure insofar as it is reasonably able to do so, provided that the terms of the settlement of any strike, lockout or other industrial disturbance shall be wholly in the discretion of the Party claiming suspension of its obligations hereunder by reason thereof. Notwithstanding the above provisions, no event of Force Majeure shall: (i) relieve any Party from any obligation or obligations unless such Party gives notice with reasonable promptness of such event to the other Party; or (ii) relieve any Party from any obligation or obligations after the expiration of a reasonable period of time within which, by the use of its due diligence, such Party could have remedied or overcome the consequences of such event of Force Majeure. 95 DISPOSITION OF SHIPMENT IF NO FACILITIES AT DESTINATION In the event Shipper does not have adequate facilities available to receive any shipment at a Point of Destination in accordance with Carrier's Tariff, Carrier may make whatever disposition of such undelivered shipment as necessary to free its pipeline facility, including the right to remove and sell such LPG in such lawful manner as deemed appropriate by Carrier. Carrier shall pay from the proceeds of such sale all costs incurred by Carrier with respect to the storage, removal and sale of such LPG. The remainder of such proceeds, if any, shall be held by Carrier for the shipper and any other party lawfully entitled to such proceeds. 100 ALLOCATION OF CARRIER'S FACILITIES When Carrier receives Nominations for the transportation of LPG in quantities greater than can be transported, Carrier shall undertake the allocation of its available facilities on an not unduly discriminatory basis and shall restrict or suspend nominations and transportation to the extent necessary to effect such allocation, in accordance with the "Laclede Pipeline Company Proration Policy" dated April 1, 2006, which is available to tariff subscribers upon request. 105 LIABILITY OF CARRIER Carrier shall not be liable to Shipper for any loss, damage consequential loss or damage, or delay caused by an event of Force Majeure, except caused by its own direct negligence. If damage to or loss of LPG results from any cause other than the direct negligence of Carrier while Carrier is in possession or control of such LPG, then Carrier may apportion the cost of such damage or loss on a pro rata basis among all Shippers. Each Shipper's share of such cost shall be determined by Carrier based on the proportion of the volume of the Shipper's LPG in the possession of Carrier on the date of such loss to the total volume of LPG in the possession of Carrier on the date of such loss. All Shippers shall be responsible for their proportionate share of physical losses of LPG resulting from normal pipeline operations, including line losses and shrinkage.
